<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=wizardbalance&message.id=2551#M2551">59</a> of 234
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 436 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>

<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>All spells will check for immunity before they are cast.&nbsp; So if the target is immune, the spell will not generate aggro for the caster.</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This made me think about concussion and ancient greater concussion.</P>
<P>From reading Graffe's and from personal experience, i have always believed that the&nbsp;aggro reduction&nbsp;effect works when the spell is cast even if the text states: "Your target resisted the ancient greater concussion spell". If this isn't the case, the concussion spell would be extremely ineffective given the frequency of the resist messages. </P>
<P>If the aggro reduction effect really&nbsp;does work when the spell is cast, regardless of the resist message, could you change the spell text to show that it is actually&nbsp;working? </P>
<P>It's a small thing but in other games, if i cast a spell, i expect to&nbsp;see clearly the results of the spell... the&nbsp;two current messages for the concussion spell appear to be misleading with respect to whether the aggro reduction effect occurs or not. It seems counter-intuitive.</P>
<P>I mention this point in light of the quote, because on Graffe's some wizards have wondered whether the proposed&nbsp;changes will have any effect on concussion.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
