		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Someone posted about max mana regen while sitting.&nbsp; I can say from experience with ft13, allegiant familiar, c6, SA, steeloak, and bard song going, I am regenning 105 mana/tick while sitting on a mount.&nbsp; This is not a sub-normal situation.&nbsp; This is typical for any raid situation, and I have found that, while grouping, I get about 85 mana/tick sitting.&nbsp; Consider that most pulls in DoN zones take about 30 seconds between fights, and most fights usually last about 2-4 minutes.&nbsp; I chain Claw of Frost at 167 base mana per cast with Preservation of Xegony (15% MP) and SCM1.&nbsp; I find that I am usually about 1-3% down on my mana per pull, and this quickly recovers for particularly difficult pulls.&nbsp; I have also found that chain nuking this spell generates little enough aggro that I can start casting as soon as a tank appears on HoTT and continue chain casting through the entire duration of the fight, up to about a 15 minute duration, without running out of mana or stealing aggro.&nbsp; At 3.6 seconds per cast, go ahead and figure out my overall damage in comparison to 2-3 casts of Thundaka per fight, with typically 1 resist per fight as well.&nbsp; Our damage isn't the issue.&nbsp; Our aggro very much is.&nbsp; Fix the amount of hate we generate and THEN we'll discuss where our DPS lies.&nbsp; If you don't believe this statement, compare the DPS of a wizard with and without EP pants.&nbsp; You will find that if a wizard without achieves the same DPS as a wizard with, then they usually end up as a stain on the boots of some big ugly in short order.&nbsp; Debuffers and wizards are struck the hardest by this issue, and as you can see from the list that was posted, debuffer aggro is being addressed.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>On a side note, I have noticed, being a wizard with spark of thunder, that groups tend to rely heavily on me for counterspells if they know I have the spell.&nbsp; While it is nice to know I have a role to play in&nbsp;xp groups (interrupting CHeals, Gates, and other very nasty spells is a major utility), this line of spells holds TREMENDOUS aggro.&nbsp; In fact, I use this spell in aggro kiting groups to solidify my aggro.&nbsp; I've tested it before, and 3 hits of spark of thunder can hold aggro with me doing nothing else until just before a mob dies at PoFire tables.&nbsp; While this isn't exactly a typical wizard nuke (very useful for kiting casters, and stopping the nastys in group situations), its one example of the severe aggro issues we as wizards may face.</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
